To find a minimum or maximum, the gradient of the constraint function $f(x, y)=\frac{x^{2}}{b^{2}}+\frac{y^{2}}{a^{2}}-1$ and the gradient of the $B$ field function should be scalar multiples of each other.

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{2 x}{b^{2}} \mu=c_{b} y e^{x y} \\
& \frac{2 y}{a^{2}} \mu=c_{b} x e^{x y}
\end{aligned}
$$

Solving the two equations, we get that a maximum point $(x, y)$ is of the form $\left(\frac{b}{\sqrt{2}}, \frac{a}{\sqrt{2}}\right)$ or $\left(-\frac{b}{\sqrt{2}},-\frac{a}{\sqrt{2}}\right)$. The distance from the $\mathrm{y}$-axis is thus $\frac{a}{\sqrt{2}}=70.7 \mathrm{~m}$.

Conservation of momentum and energy gives:
$$
\begin{gathered}
p_{m}=2 E_{\gamma} \cos (\theta / 2) \\
E_{m}=2 E_{\gamma}
\end{gathered}
$$

Relativity demands that:

$$
E_{m}^{2}=m^{2}+p_{m}^{2}
$$

Solving this system of three equations gives:

$$
\begin{aligned}
4 E_{\gamma}^{2} & =m^{2}+p_{m}^{2} \\
\frac{\gamma^{2} m^{2} v^{2}}{\cos ^{2}(\theta / 2)} & =m^{2}+\gamma^{2} m^{2} v^{2} \\
\gamma^{2} v^{2}\left(-1+\frac{1}{\cos ^{2}(\theta / 2)}\right) & =1 \\
\frac{1}{\cos ^{2}(\theta / 2)} & =\frac{1}{\gamma^{2} v^{2}}+1 \\
\cos (\theta / 2) & =v \\
\theta & =91.1^{\circ}
\end{aligned}
$$

One can solve this by finding the time it takes for each ramp. For ramp 1:
$$
\begin{aligned}
\sqrt{2} & =\frac{1}{2} g \sin \left(45^{\circ}\right) t^{2} \\
\Longrightarrow t & =0.639 \mathrm{~s}
\end{aligned}
$$

For ramps 2, let the length of the dashed region be $x$. Then:

$$
x+x / \tan \left(30^{\circ}\right)=1 \Longrightarrow x=0.366 \mathrm{~m}
\tag{1}
$$

Due to symmetry, both the steep and shallow regions of both ramps 2 and 3 have a length of $x / \cos \left(60^{\circ}\right)=0.732 \mathrm{~m}$. This results in a time for ramp 2 as:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& 0.732=\frac{1}{2} g \sin \left(60^{\circ}\right) t_{1}^{2} \Longrightarrow t_{1}=0.415 \mathrm{~s} \\
& 0.732=\sqrt{2 g(1-x)} t_{2}+\frac{1}{2} g \sin \left(30^{\circ}\right) t_{2}^{2} \Longrightarrow t_{2}=0.184 \mathrm{~s}
\end{aligned}
$$

for a total time of $t_{1}+t_{2}=0.599 \mathrm{~s}$. For ramp 3 ,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& 0.732=\frac{1}{2} g \sin \left(30^{\circ}\right) t_{1}^{2} \Longrightarrow t_{1}=0.546 \mathrm{~s} \\
& 0.732=\sqrt{2 g(1-x)} t_{2}+\frac{1}{2} g \sin \left(60^{\circ}\right) t_{2}^{2} \Longrightarrow t_{2}=0.206 \mathrm{~s}
\end{aligned}
$$

which gives a total time of $t_{1}+t_{2}=0.752 \mathrm{~s}$. From fastest to slowest, the answer becomes 213 . Note that this answer is easily guessable via intuition.

The speed at which Alice's car hits the ground is given by $v_{A}=\sqrt{2 g(1)}=4.43 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}$ from energy conservation. The speed at which Bob's car hits the ground is given by $v_{B}=$ $\sqrt{2 g\left(1-0.1 \sin \left(45^{\circ}\right)\right.}=4.27 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}$ since its center of mass is at the very front of the car.


The time in which Alice and Bob's cars are going down the ramp (and wheels are both on the ramp) is given by:

$$
\sqrt{2}-0.1=\frac{1}{2} g \sin \left(45^{\circ}\right) t^{2} \Longrightarrow t=0.616 \mathrm{~s}
\tag{3}
$$

And the time that Alice's car takes on the flat path (and wheels are both on the floor) is given by $t_{A}=\frac{20}{v_{A}}=4.51$, and for Bob, $t_{B}=\frac{20}{v_{B}}=4.68$.

We ignore the time it takes for the car to transition. The justification behind this is that this time would be on the order of magnitude of $\frac{0.1}{v_{A}}=0.02 \mathrm{~s} \ll t_{A}$. In fact, it is smaller than the $1 \%$ margin allowed (so teams who did not read the clarification would still have gotten the correct answer). The ratio asked for was therefore:

$$
\frac{0.616+t_{B}}{0.616+t_{A}}
\tag{4}
$$

question:
Consider a gas of mysterious particles called nieons that all travel at the same speed, $v$. They are enclosed in a cubical box, and there are $\rho$ nieons per unit volume. A very small hole of area $A$ is punched in the side of the box. The number of nieons that escape the box per unit time is given by
$$
\alpha v^{\beta} A^{\gamma} \rho^{\delta}
\tag{10}
$$

where $\alpha, \beta, \gamma$, and $\delta$ are all dimensionless constants. Calculate $\alpha+\beta+\gamma+\delta$.

solution:
Using conservation of energy, the minimum initial velocity of the ball needed to pass the top of the track is $v_{a}=\sqrt{2 g h}=9.9045 \frac{\mathrm{m}}{\mathrm{s}}$. To find $v_{b}$, the centripetal force at all points on the track must be determined given the initial velocity.
$$

F_{c} =\frac{m v^{2}}{R}
\tag{11}
$$
$$
=\frac{m\left(v_{b}^{2}-2 g h\right)}{\frac{\left|1+\left(\frac{d}{d x} h(x)\right)^{2}\right|}{\frac{d^{2}}{d x^{2}} h(x)}}
\tag{12}
$$
$$
=\frac{m\left(v_{b}^{2}-2 g h\right)}{\frac{\left|1+16 x^{2}\right|^{\frac{3}{2}}}{4}}
\tag{13}
$$

For the boundary condition, the ball leaves if the normal force from the track on the ball $N=m g \cos \theta-F_{c}$ becomes 0.

$$
\begin{aligned}
m g \cos \theta-F_{c} & =0 \\
m g \cos \arctan (-4 x) & =\frac{4 m\left(v_{b}^{2}-2 g h\right)}{\left|1+16 x^{2}\right|^{\frac{3}{2}}} \\
\frac{g}{\left|1+16 x^{2}\right|^{\frac{1}{2}}} & =\frac{4\left(v_{b}^{2}-2 g h\right)}{\left|1+16 x^{2}\right|^{\frac{3}{2}}} \\
g & =\frac{4\left(v_{b}^{2}-2 g h\right)}{1+16 x^{2}} \\
v_{b \max } & =\sqrt{\frac{g+16 g x^{2}}{4}+2 g h}
\end{aligned}
$$

From the derivation, $v_{b \max }$ is the lowest at $x=0$. Thus,

$$
\begin{aligned}
v_{b \max } & =\sqrt{\frac{g}{4}+2 g h} \\
& =10.0276 \frac{\mathrm{m}}{\mathrm{s}}
\end{aligned}
$$

which is our desired $v_{b}$. The final answer, $v_{b}-v_{a}$, can be calculated.

The key claim is that energy is minimized when both particles are moving at the same velocity after the collision. This can be proved by transforming into the frame where the total momentum is 0 .
This idea is sufficient because it implies both the electron and positron have the same momentum and energy after the collision. Let them both have momentum $p$. We then have

$$
2 p=\frac{E_{\gamma_{1}}-E_{\gamma_{2}}}{c} \Longrightarrow p c=\frac{E_{\gamma_{1}}-E_{\gamma_{2}}}{2}
\tag{21}
$$

By energy conservation, both the electron and positron have energy $\frac{E_{\gamma_{1}}+E_{\gamma_{2}}}{2}$. Using the result $E=(p c)^{2}+\left(m c^{2}\right)^{2}$, we obtain,

$$
\left(\frac{E_{\gamma_{1}}+E_{\gamma_{2}}}{2}\right)^{2}=(p c)^{2}+\left(m_{e} c^{2}\right)^{2}
\tag{22}
$$

Combining equation 21 and equation 22 , we get

$$
\left(\frac{E_{\gamma_{1}}+E_{\gamma_{2}}}{2}\right)^{2}=\left(\frac{E_{\gamma_{1}}-E_{\gamma_{2}}}{2}\right)^{2}+\left(m_{e} c^{2}\right)^{2} \Longrightarrow E_{\gamma_{2}}=\frac{m_{e}^{2} c^{4}}{E_{\gamma_{1}}}
$$

In the mirror's frame of reference, the source speed and the image speed is both $u+v$ but in opposite direction. Now, go back the the observer's frame of reference, the image speed becomes $v^{\prime}$ :
$$
v^{\prime}=(u+v)+u=2 u+v=8 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}
\tag{1}
$$

In this setting, for every orientation during rotation the total magnetic flux passing though MNPP'N'M' is tthe same as through MPP'M', which has area $S=\sqrt{2} L^{2}$.
The magnetic flux is:

$$
\Phi(t)=B S \sin (\omega t)=\sqrt{2} B L^{2} \sin (\omega t) .
\tag{3}
$$

The emf running around the wire-frame is:

$$
E(t)=\frac{d}{d t} \Phi(t)=\sqrt{2} B L^{2} \omega \cos (\omega t)
\tag{4}
$$

The electrical current running around the wire-frame is:

$$
I(t)=\frac{E(t)}{6 \lambda L}=\frac{B L \omega \cos (\omega t)}{3 \sqrt{2} \lambda}
\tag{5}
$$

The heat released power is:

$$
\frac{d}{d t} Q(t)=I^{2}(t) \times 6 \lambda L=\frac{B^{2} L^{3} \omega^{2} \cos ^{2}(\omega t)}{3 \lambda}
\tag{6}
$$

Thus the total heat released per revolution is:

$$
Q=\int_{0}^{2 \pi / \omega} d t \frac{d}{d t} Q(t)=\frac{B^{2} L^{3} \omega^{2} \int_{0}^{2 \pi / \omega} d t \cos ^{2}(\omega t)}{3 \lambda}=\frac{\pi B^{2} L^{3} \omega}{3 \lambda} \approx 6.58 \mathrm{~J}
\tag{7}
$$

The total heat gain is equal to the change in potential energy of the raindrop, which spreads through out the whole environment at thermally equilibrium temperature $T$ (the environment is very large so any change in $T$ is negligible). The entropy gain $\Delta S$ is thus generated by the dissipation of this potential energy $M g H$ to internal energy $\Delta U$ in the environment (given that the specific volume of water doesn't change much, $\Delta U \approx M g H$ ). Hence the entropy change associated with this process can be estimated by:
$$
S=\frac{\Delta U}{T} \approx \frac{M g H}{T} \approx 2.29 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{K}
\tag{8}
$$

We call the current looping in the wires $I_{1}, I_{2}, I_{3}, I_{4}$ as shown in the attached Fig., and define the resistance of every quarter-circular section (radius $R$ ) of the wires to be $\rho$, then considering the



EMF on every loop gives:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \left(2 I_{1}+\left(I_{1}-I_{2}\right)-I_{4}\right) \rho=\frac{d B_{\perp}}{d t} \times \frac{\pi+2}{2} R^{2} \\
& \left(2 I_{2}-I_{3}-\left(I_{1}-I_{2}\right)\right) \rho=\frac{d B_{\perp}}{d t} \times \frac{\pi+2}{2} R^{2} \\
& \left(2 I_{4}+2\left(I_{1}-I_{2}-I_{3}+I_{4}\right)\right) \rho=\frac{d B_{\perp}}{d t} \times 2 R^{2} \\
& \left(2 I_{3}-2\left(I_{1}-I_{2}-I_{3}+I_{4}\right)\right) \rho=\frac{d B_{\perp}}{d t} \times 2 R^{2}
\end{aligned}
\tag{9}
$$

in which $B_{\perp}$ is the perpendicular component of the magnetic field.

![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2023_12_21_6bda60f521822c3b3f7eg-1.jpg?height=781&width=786&top_left_y=778&top_left_x=664)

The set of equations in Eq. (9) can be solved to get the relation between currents:

$$
I_{1}=I_{2}, I_{3}=I_{4}, \frac{I_{1}}{I_{3}}=\frac{\pi+4}{4}
\tag{10}
$$

The fraction of heat released on the outermost wires can be calculated:

$$
\frac{Q_{\text {outermost }}}{Q_{\text {all }}}=\frac{\left(8 I_{1}^{2}+8 I_{2}^{2}\right) \rho}{\left(8 I_{1}^{2}+8 I_{2}^{2}+4 I_{3}^{2}+4 I_{4}^{2}\right) \rho}=\frac{(\pi+4)^{2}}{(\pi+4)^{2}+8} \approx 0.864 \mathrm{~J}
\tag{11}
$$

We define the angles as in Fig. A. The light-path inside the optical system is $r(\theta)$, and the angle between the first and last lens is $\Theta$ (which is an unknown but can be uniquely determined from know information).


![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2023_12_21_1dc8e68f97c9d182f754g-1.jpg?height=694&width=1484&top_left_y=225&top_left_x=316)

Consider two consecutive lens at angle $\theta$ and $\theta+d \theta$, in which $d \theta=1 / n \rightarrow 0$ in the continuum limit $n \rightarrow \infty$. From the ideal-lens' equation, using the approximation that $f$ is very large compare to other relevant length-scales in this optical setting:

$$
\frac{1}{f}=\frac{1}{r \tan \phi}+\frac{1}{r \tan (\pi-\phi-\delta \phi)} \approx \frac{\delta \phi}{r \sin ^{2} \phi} \Rightarrow \delta \phi \approx \frac{r}{f} \sin ^{2} \phi
\tag{20}
$$

the differential equation for the angle of arrival $\phi$ can be written as:

$$
d \phi=\delta \phi-d \theta \Rightarrow \frac{d \phi}{d \theta}=\frac{r}{f / n} \sin ^{2} \phi-1=\frac{r}{\lambda} \sin ^{2} \phi-1
\tag{21}
$$

We also have the differential relation between radial position $r(\theta)$ of the light-path and the angle of arrival $\phi$ as followed:

$$
\frac{d r}{d \theta}=r \cot \phi
\tag{22}
$$

From Eq. (21) and Eq. (22), we arrive at:

$$
\frac{d \phi}{d r}=\frac{\frac{r}{\lambda}-1}{r \cot \phi}
\tag{23}
$$

Define $\zeta=\tan \phi$, then Eq. (23) becomes:

$$
\frac{d \phi}{d r}=\frac{1}{1+\zeta^{2}} \frac{d \zeta}{d r}=\frac{\frac{r}{\lambda} \frac{\zeta^{2}}{1+\zeta^{2}}-1}{r / \zeta} \Rightarrow-\frac{d \zeta}{\zeta^{3} d r}-\frac{1}{\zeta^{2} r}=\frac{1}{r}-\frac{1}{\lambda}
\tag{24}
$$

Define $\xi=1 / \zeta^{2}=1 / \tan ^{2} \phi$, then Eq. (23) gives:

$$
\frac{d \zeta}{\zeta^{2} d r}=-\frac{1}{2} \frac{d \xi}{d r} \Rightarrow \frac{d \xi}{d r}-\frac{2}{r} \xi=2\left(\frac{1}{r}-\frac{1}{\lambda}\right) \Rightarrow \frac{d}{d r}\left(\frac{\xi}{r^{2}}\right)=\frac{2}{r^{2}}\left(\frac{1}{r}-\frac{1}{\lambda}\right)
\tag{25}
$$

Integrating both sides, then up to a constant value $C$, Eq. (25) gives:

$$
\frac{\xi}{r^{2}}=-\frac{1}{r^{2}}+\frac{2}{\lambda r}+C \Rightarrow \xi=-1+2 \frac{r}{\lambda}+C \frac{r^{2}}{\lambda^{2}}
\tag{26}
$$



At $\theta=0, r=\lambda / 2$ and $\phi=\pi / 2$ (thus $\xi=0$ ), we can determine $C=0$. Hence:

$$
\cot \phi=\sqrt{2 \frac{r}{\lambda}-1}
\tag{27}
$$

Plug Eq. (27) into Eq. (22):

$$
\frac{d r}{d \theta}=\frac{r}{\lambda} \sqrt{2 \frac{r}{\lambda}-1} \Rightarrow \theta=2 \arctan \sqrt{2 \frac{r}{\lambda}-1}
\tag{28}
$$

At $\theta=\Theta, r=2 \lambda$ therefore we can use Eq. (28) to get:

$$
\Theta=2 \arctan \sqrt{3}=\frac{2 \pi}{3}
\tag{29}
$$

Using Eq. (27), the deflection angle $\Delta$ can be calculated to be:

$$
\Delta=\Theta-\left.\phi\right|_{r=\lambda / 2}+\left.\phi\right|_{r=2 \lambda}=\Theta-\frac{\pi}{2}+\operatorname{arccot} \sqrt{3}=\frac{2 \pi}{3}-\frac{\pi}{2}+\frac{\pi}{6}=\frac{\pi}{3} \approx 1.05 \mathrm{rad}
\tag{30}
$$

