1. Determination of $\mathrm{B}$ :

The vector of the velocity of any electron is divided into components parallel with and perpendicular to the magnetic field $\overrightarrow{\mathrm{B}}$ :

$$
\overrightarrow{\mathrm{v}}=\overrightarrow{\mathrm{v}}_{\|}+\overrightarrow{\mathrm{v}}_{\perp}
\tag{1}
$$

The Lorentz force $\overrightarrow{\mathrm{F}}=-\mathrm{e} \cdot(\overrightarrow{\mathrm{v}} \times \overrightarrow{\mathrm{B}})$ influences only the perpendicular component, it acts as a radial force:

$$
\mathrm{m} \cdot \frac{\mathrm{v}_{\perp}^{2}}{\mathrm{r}}=\mathrm{e} \cdot \mathrm{v}_{\perp} \cdot \mathrm{B}
\tag{2}
$$

Hence the radius of the circular path that has been travelled is

$$
\mathrm{r}=\frac{\mathrm{m}}{\mathrm{e}} \cdot \frac{\mathrm{v}_{\perp}}{\mathrm{B}}
\tag{3}
$$



and the period of rotation which is independent of $\mathrm{v}_{\perp}$ is

$$
\mathrm{T}=\frac{2 \cdot \pi \cdot \mathrm{r}}{\mathrm{v}_{\perp}}=\frac{2 \cdot \pi \cdot \mathrm{m}}{\mathrm{B} \cdot \mathrm{e}}
\tag{4}
$$

The parallel component of the velocity does not vary. Because of $\alpha_{0}<<1$ it is approximately equal for all electrons:

$$
\mathrm{V}_{\| 0}=\mathrm{V}_{0} \cdot \cos \alpha_{0} \approx \mathrm{v}_{0}
\tag{5}
$$

Hence the distance $b$ between the focusing points, using eq. (5), is

$$
\mathrm{b}=\mathrm{v}_{\| 0} \cdot \mathrm{T} \approx \mathrm{v}_{0} \cdot \mathrm{T}
\tag{6}
$$

From the law of conservation of energy follows the relation between the acceleration voltage $\mathrm{V}_{0}$ and the velocity $\mathrm{v}_{0}$ :

$$
\frac{\mathrm{m}}{2} \cdot \mathrm{v}_{0}^{2}=\mathrm{e} \cdot \mathrm{V}_{0}
\tag{7}
$$

Using eq. (7) and eq. (4) one obtains from eq. (6)

$$
\mathrm{b}=\frac{2 \cdot \pi}{\mathrm{B}} \cdot \sqrt{2 \cdot \frac{\mathrm{m}}{\mathrm{e}} \cdot \mathrm{V}_{0}}
\tag{8}
$$

and because of $b=\frac{2 \cdot \pi \cdot R}{4}$ one obtains

$$
\mathrm{B}=\frac{4}{\mathrm{R}} \cdot \sqrt{2 \cdot \frac{\mathrm{m}}{\mathrm{e}} \cdot \mathrm{V}_{0}}=1.48 \cdot 10^{-2} \frac{\mathrm{Vs}}{\mathrm{m}^{2}}
\tag{9}
$$

2. Determination of $\mathrm{B}_{1}$ :

Analogous to eq. (2)

$$
\mathrm{m} \cdot \frac{\mathrm{v}_{0}^{2}}{\mathrm{R}}=\mathrm{e} \cdot \mathrm{v}_{0} \cdot \mathrm{B}_{1}
\tag{10}
$$

must hold.

From eq. (7) follows

$$
\mathrm{B}_{1}=\frac{1}{\mathrm{R}} \cdot \sqrt{2 \cdot \frac{\mathrm{m}}{\mathrm{e}} \cdot \mathrm{V}_{0}}=0.37 \cdot 10^{-2} \frac{\mathrm{Vs}}{\mathrm{m}^{2}}
\tag{11}
$$

