$$

Energy (3) of the question sheet can be interpreted as describing a system of a mass $\mu$ in a circular orbit with angular velocity $\Omega$, radius $L$, around a mass $M$ (at rest). Equating the gravitational acceleration to the centripetal acceleration:

$$
G \frac{M}{L^{2}}=\Omega^{2} L
\tag{8}
$$

This is indeed Kepler's third law (for circular orbits). Then, from 7,

$$
E=-\frac{1}{2} G \frac{M \mu}{L}
\tag{9}
$$

Some simple trigonometry for the $x, y$ motion of the masses (in an appropriate Cartesian system) yields:

$$
\left(x_{1}, y_{1}\right)=r_{1}(\cos (\Omega t), \sin (\Omega t)), \quad\left(x_{2}, y_{2}\right)=-r_{2}(\cos (\Omega t), \sin (\Omega t))
\tag{10}
$$

Then,

$$
Q_{i j}=\frac{M_{1} r_{1}^{2}+M_{2} r_{2}^{2}}{2}\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
\frac{4}{3} \cos ^{2}(\Omega t)-\frac{2}{3} \sin ^{2}(\Omega t) & 2 \sin (\Omega t) \cos (\Omega t) & 0 \\
2 \sin (\Omega t) \cos (\Omega t) & \frac{4}{3} \sin ^{2}(\Omega t)-\frac{2}{3} \cos ^{2}(\Omega t) & 0 \\
0 & 0 & -\frac{2}{3}
\end{array}\right)
\tag{11}
$$

or, using some simple trigonometry and (6),

$$
Q_{i j}=\frac{\mu L^{2}}{2}\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
\frac{1}{3}+\cos 2 \Omega t & \sin 2 \Omega t & 0 \\
